description: From Middle English arce-hoole, equivalent to arse +‎ hole. Compare Old English ears-þerl (“anus”, literally “arse-hole”).

entries.meaning: (Britain, Australia, Ireland, New Zealand, Canada (regional), mildly vulgar) The anus.
examples: The moment I sat on the toilet, my crap immediately came out of my arsehole.

entries.meaning: (mildly vulgar, offensive) An inconsiderate or mean-spirited person. Less vulgar and intense than fucker or cunt.
examples: Shut up, you big dummy! – Hey! Don't call me “big dummy”, you arsehole!

entries.meaning: (UK, vulgar, uncountable) A variant of the card game big two.
(vulgar) Alternative form of asshole (“anything unpleasant or undesirable”)
